Let me write this now.I remember the first time infinity felt real. I was seven, staring at two mirrors angled just so, watching myself recede into smaller and smaller versions, each one watching the next. I moved my finger, and a thousand tiny fingers moved in unison, and I thought: *it goes on forever*. But even then, I sensed the lie—the reflections would fade when the light ran out of energy, when the photons grew too tired to bounce. Infinity, I learned, is always hemmed in by physics.

Later, mathematics gave me a crueler, more beautiful truth. Georg Cantor, in his asylum room, proved that some infinities are *bigger* than others. The counting numbers—1, 2, 3, stretching on forever—are infinite, yes. But the real numbers between 0 and 1? That infinity is *vaster*, so dense that no clever trick can pair each one with a counting number. The rationals are a crowded elevator that never fills; the irrationals are an endless continent where every step lands on uncharted soil.

This is infinity's true terror: not that it goes on, but that it *ramifies*. There is infinity upon infinity, an infinite tower of infinities, each one unreachable from the one below. The set of all subsets of an infinite set is always a larger infinity. You can keep climbing this ladder forever, but the ladder itself is infinite, and there are infinite ladders.

Cosmologists tell us the universe might be infinite. If so, everything that can happen, happens—not once, but infinitely many times. There are infinite copies of you, reading infinite copies of this text, on a planet identical to Earth, in a galaxy identical to ours, somewhere in the unreachably distant cosmos. But here's the poetry: even in an infinite universe, you might never meet your double. The space between you could be expanding faster than light can travel, a gulf of inflating nothingness that no bridge can cross. Infinity doesn't guarantee reunion; it guarantees solitude.

Zeno knew this. His arrow never reaches the target because the distance can be halved, then halved again, forever. We dismiss it as a trick of calculus, but the paradox holds in the muscles of the archer, the tension of the string. The infinite series converges, but the *feeling* of it—of infinite steps in finite time—never quite resolves. We live it every second: the present moment is a limit approaching itself, never quite arriving.

And then there's the infinity inside. The human brain has roughly 86 billion neurons, making roughly 100 trillion connections. That's not infinite. But the *states* it can take, the configurations of firing and resting, might as well be. You could live a thousand lifetimes and never think the same thought twice. Consciousness is a finite machine simulating infinity, a closed loop that feels endless from within.

I think about the Library of Babel, Borges' infinite archive containing every possible book. Most are gibberish, but somewhere—somewhere—there is a perfect index of all the others. And next to it, a book that indexes the indexes, and another that indexes those, and so on. The library contains its own catalogue, but the catalogue requires its own catalogue, and that one another, forever. Even infinity cannot organize itself.

Perhaps the deepest infinity is the simplest: the ellipsis at the end of thought. Every answer births a question; every explanation demands its own explanation. Children know this, asking "why?" until the adult snaps. The chain doesn't break because the answers run out—it breaks because our patience does. The universe has no such impatience. It *is* the endless "why."

So I return to the mirrors. The reflections fade, but the *idea* of them doesn't. Infinity lives not in the physical world but in the gap between what is and what could be. It's the set of all paths not taken, branching infinitely from every moment. You are the convergence point of an infinite past (every choice that led to you) and the divergence point of an infinite future (every choice you will make). You are the finite moment where infinities collide.

